04111nam a22006375i 9780292737785DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212012txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2012010950  a97802927377857 a10.7560/7377782doi  a(DE-B1597)587371  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aPQ7297.G3585bZ64 2012 7aLIT0041002bisacsh04a868/.64091 aCypess, Sandra Messinger, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUncivil Wars :bElena Garro, Octavio Paz, and the Battle for Cultural Memory /cSandra Messinger Cypess. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2012  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- t1. Introduction: Uncivil Wars -- t2. All in the Family: Paz and Garro Rewrite Mexico’s Cultural Memory -- t3. War at Home: Betrayals of/in the Mexican Revolution -- t4. Love and War Don’t Mix: Garro and Paz in the Spanish Civil War -- t5. Tlatelolco: The Undeclared War -- t6. From Civil War to Gender War: The Battle of the Sexes -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first English-language book to place the works of Elena Garro (1916–1998) and Octavio Paz (1914–1998) in dialogue with each other, Uncivil Wars evokes the lives of two celebrated literary figures who wrote about many of the same experiences and contributed to the formation of Mexican national identity but were judged quite differently, primarily because of gender. While Paz’s privileged, prize-winning legacy has endured worldwide, Garro’s literary gifts garnered no international prizes and received less attention in Latin American literary circles. Restoring a dual perspective on these two dynamic writers and their world, Uncivil Wars chronicles a collective memory of wars that shaped Mexico, and in turn shaped Garro and Paz, from the Conquest period to the Mexican Revolution; the Spanish Civil War, which the couple witnessed while traveling abroad; and the student massacre at Tlatelolco Plaza in 1968, which brought about social and political changes and further tensions in the battle of the sexes. The cultural contexts of machismo and ethnicity provide an equally rich ground for Sandra Cypess’s exploration of the tandem between the writers’ personal lives and their literary production. Uncivil Wars illuminates the complexities of Mexican society as seen through a tense marriage of two talented, often oppositional writers. The result is an alternative interpretation of the myths and realities that have shaped Mexican identity, and its literary soul, well into the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCollective memoryzMexico. 0aNational characteristics, Mexican, in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73777840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292737785423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292737785/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK